‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Step 1 ‚Äî Power ON

Electricity reaches motherboard.

CPU resets and executes firmware from ROM.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ Step 2 ‚Äî BIOS / UEFI

BIOS = Basic Input Output System.

Performs:
	‚Ä¢	CPU initialization
	‚Ä¢	RAM check
	‚Ä¢	PCI device detection
	‚Ä¢	Storage detection

This phase called POST.

‚∏ª

BIOS selects boot device

Example:
	‚Ä¢	SSD
	‚Ä¢	USB
	‚Ä¢	Network PXE

Loads bootloader from disk.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ Step 3 ‚Äî Bootloader (GRUB)

GRUB = Grand Unified Bootloader.

Responsibilities:
	‚Ä¢	Shows boot menu
	‚Ä¢	Selects OS
	‚Ä¢	Loads kernel
	‚Ä¢	Passes boot arguments

Files located in:

/boot/grub


‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£6Ô∏è‚É£ Step 4 ‚Äî Kernel Loading

GRUB loads kernel image:

vmlinuz

Into RAM and executes it.

Kernel decompresses itself.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£7Ô∏è‚É£ Step 5 ‚Äî Initramfs

Temporary root filesystem loaded into RAM.

Contains:
	‚Ä¢	Essential drivers
	‚Ä¢	Storage modules
	‚Ä¢	Mount tools

Used to prepare real rootfs.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£8Ô∏è‚É£ Step 6 ‚Äî Root Filesystem Mount

Kernel mounts permanent root filesystem:

/ (root)

Contains:
	‚Ä¢	/bin
	‚Ä¢	/sbin
	‚Ä¢	/lib
	‚Ä¢	/etc
	‚Ä¢	/usr

Now full OS accessible.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£9Ô∏è‚É£ Step 7 ‚Äî Init System (systemd)

Kernel starts first user-space process:

PID 1 ‚Üí systemd

systemd manages:
	‚Ä¢	Services
	‚Ä¢	Daemons
	‚Ä¢	Targets (runlevels)

‚∏ª

2Ô∏è‚É£0Ô∏è‚É£ Step 8 ‚Äî Service Startup

systemd launches:
	‚Ä¢	Networking
	‚Ä¢	SSH
	‚Ä¢	Logging
	‚Ä¢	Hardware services

System becomes operational.

‚∏ª

